 resonances between contemporary artistic ideas and the indigenous sources of Chinese cultural self-understanding.Focusing in particular on the acclaimed artist Xu Bing, this book looks at how he and his peers have navigated between two different cultural sites to establish a third place, a place from which to appropriate Western ideas and use them to address centuries-old Chinese cultural issues within a Chinese cultural discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArt, Chinese -- 20th century -- Themes, motives. 0aArt, Chinese -- 21st century -- Themes, motives. 0aArt, Chinesey20th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aArt, Chinesey21st centuryxThemes, motives. 0aXu, Bing, -- 1955- -- Criticism and interpretation. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Art. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Eastern / General.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmes, Roger T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChang, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Kuan-Hung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKameda-Madar, Kazuko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Zoe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiu, April, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilbergeld, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsao, Hsingyuan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsao, Hsingyuan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVinograd, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id